                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1002">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">711.417/1139: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-06-06T14:00:00+03:00"
                            >June 6, 1941—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received June 6—12:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1095. Department’s 748, May 29, 7 p.m.<note n="22" xml:id="d1002fn1">Not
                        printed.</note> In my conversation with Lozovski<note n="23"
                        xml:id="d1002fn2">Solomon A. Lozovski, Soviet Assistant Commissar for
                        Foreign Affairs.</note> yesterday evening I raised the question of the Fur
                    Seal Convention. He said that the Soviet Government is in the process of
                    drafting its reply to the Japanese Government and that he would advise me of its
                    nature in the course of the next few days. He seemed entirely agreeable to the
                    renewal of the subject between the United States and the Soviet Union.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Steinhardt</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
